In Nigeria, faith is a cornerstone of daily life. Whether among Muslims who pray five times a day or Christians who are deeply involved in their church communities, spirituality is not just a Sunday or Friday activity—it is the lens through which we view existence, success, and even the problems we face. While we recognize the importance of science, particularly in medicine and education, there is a strong cultural belief that science provides only part of the picture.

We often say, "Man proposes, but God disposes." We go to the hospital when sick, but we pray for the hands of the doctor to be guided, and we trust in divine intervention for outcomes that science cannot explain. Many Nigerians feel that the modern world has become increasingly focused on materialism and "book knowledge" at the expense of our reliance on God, which we believe is the true source of our endurance, social cohesion, and ultimate protection. Because our culture teaches us that human wisdom is limited and that faith is the foundation of moral character and hope in challenging times, there is a strong sentiment that relying solely on earthly science, without a spiritual anchor, leaves us morally and spiritually vulnerable.

